Massive sell-offs persists as the local equities market further dipped on Wednesday to record N1.411 trillion loss since the beginning of the week, as the market continued to react to the outbreak of Coronavirus as well as the crude oil collapse. On Wednesday, The All-Share Index (ASI) decreased by 815.91 absolute points, representing a dip of 3.35 per cent to close at 23,572.75 points. Similarly, the overall Market Capitalisation size shed N425.2 billion, representing a dip of 4.91 per cent to close at N12.28 trillion. Consequent to weak sentiments in the domestic equities market as investors sell-off of bellwether stock dampened market performance, Month-to-Date and Year-to-Date losses at -10.1 per cent and -12.2 per cent, respectively. ALSO READ: Coronavirus: Nigerians at risk as 150m lack access to handwashing facilities ― WaterAid Also, the market breadth closed negative, recording 18 gainers against 20 losers with Chams and Courtville emerging top gainer with ten per cent appreciation while Dangote Cement and Nestle Nigeria topped the losers’ chart with ten per cent decline in their share values. The total volume of trades increased by 134.0 per cent to 1.39 billion units, valued at N17.65 billion and exchanged in 7,150 deals. Zenith Bank was the most traded stock by volume at 412.41 million units while Guaranty Trust Bank was the most traded stock by value at NGN7.24 billion respectively. All sector indices recorded declines save for the Insurance (+2.2%) index, as the Consumer Goods (-4.7%), Industrial Goods (-3.4%), Banking (-2.7%), and Oil & Gas (-0.7) indices declined. SHOCKING LIFE STORY!!! Abuja Man reveals (FREE) secret Fruits that Increased his Manh0d size and Lasting Power in just 7days… CLICK HERE TO GET IT!!! HERE IS HOW OVER 5000  NIGERIA MEN HAVE PERMANENTLY OVERCOME TERRIBLE BEDROOM PERFORMANCE DUE TO THIS RECENT DISCOVERY BY MEDICAL CONSULTANTS